  "response_text": "A high-protein dinner that incorporates traditional South Indian flavors sounds like a great idea. Here's a suggestion:\n\n**Menu:**\n\n1. **Paruppu Rasam** (Lentil Soup) - made with a mix of lentils like toor dal, moong dal, and chana dal, which are high in protein.\n2. **Chicken or Fish Fry** - marinated in a mix of spices like turmeric, cumin, coriander, and chili powder, and then fried until crispy. You can use chicken or fish like pomfret or tilapia.\n3. **Mixed Vegetable Thoran** - a stir-fry made with a variety of vegetables like carrots, beans, cabbage, and peas, along with some protein-rich legumes like chickpeas or black-eyed peas.\n4. **Curd Rice** - a simple and comforting dish made with yogurt, rice, and a sprinkle of grated coconut.\n\n**Protein-rich ingredients:**\n\n* Lentils (paruppu) - 18g of protein per 100g serving\n* Chicken or Fish - 25-30g of protein per 100g serving\n* Chickpeas or Black-eyed peas - 9-10g of protein per 100g serving\n* Yogurt (curd) - 10g of protein per 100g serving\n\n**Tips:**\n\n* Use a combination of lentils to increase the protein content of the paruppu rasam.\n* Marinate the chicken or fish in a mixture of spices and yogurt to increase the protein content and tenderness.\n* Add some nuts or seeds like almonds, walnuts, or pumpkin seeds to the mixed vegetable thoran for an extra boost of protein.\n* Use brown rice instead of white rice to increase the fiber and protein content of the curd rice.\n\nThis menu offers a balanced and protein-rich dinner that incorporates traditional South Indian flavors and ingredients. Enjoy!",
